(And not pillow)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 19, 5, 47, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'risehr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 654753191, 'comment_body': "I actually created this yml env file purposefully to help in the creating of a new environment for anybody wanting to test my code. It's not needed later. (I guess I should remove this now.)", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 19, 5, 48, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'risehr', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 656964093, 'comment_body': 'Your loop in here does not contain everything you have in your capture loop.
The FPS you get here are always higher than your computer is able to produce, since the capture loop also writes to the mp4 file and is thus slower.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 10, 26, 10, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Marilyth', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 656971729, 'comment_body': 'Regardless of your FPS calculation, the time to record and write and image fluctuates and creates inconsistent results.
To achieve somewhat consistent FPS during your recording, it would make sense to keep track of the captured frames vs expected frames.
You can then duplicate old frames or wait additional time to exactly match your desired FPS.
Here I have a suggestion on how to do that:
```suggestion
    def capture(self):
        """
        Captures the frames of the screen at the rate of fps frames/second and writes into the
        video writer object with the defined fourcc, codec and colour format.
        """
        with mss.mss() as sct:
            bbox = {"top": 0, "left": 0, "width": self.width, "height": self.height}
            self.start_rec_time = time.time()
            frame_time_ms = 1000 / self.fps
            frames = 0
            print(f"Starting to record with FPS value {self.fps} ...")
            while self.record:
                img = sct.grab(bbox)
                img_np = np.array(img)
                img_final = cv2.cvtColor(img_np, cv2.COLOR_RGBA2RGB)
                cv2.imshow(self.window_name, img_final)
                self.recorded_video.write(img_final)

                frames += 1
                expected_frames = ((time.time() - self.start_rec_time) * 1000) / frame_time_ms
                surplus = frames - expected_frames
                
                # Duplicate previous frame to meet FPS quota. Consider lowering the FPS instead!
                if int(surplus) <= -1:
                    frames -= int(surplus)
                    for i in range(int(-surplus)):
                        self.recorded_video.write(img_final)

                # Exits the screen capturing when user press 'q'
                if cv2.waitKey(max(int(surplus * frame_time_ms), 1)) & 0xFF == ord('q'):
                    break
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 6, 23, 10, 37, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Marilyth', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Waypoints Tutorial : Working on Linux system now.
pr_body:
I have made the code more efficient in terms of automation.
Now, it has been made to work and tried both on windows and linux systems (also will work on mac)

Made the clicking points relative to the buttons which were absolute points earlier. This is helpful because different systems has the opened topview window at different positions on the screen.

On Linux system type on the terminal:
`sudo apt-get install scrot`
This will make sure the locateOnScreen functions work correctly on linux.

pr_body:
Completed the Web Map Service Automated Tutorials.
It is tested on Windows and Linux both.
As of now, the cursor is visible in Screen Recordings in Windows but in Linux, the cursor is not visible in the tutorials recording (But if screenrecorder.py is run separately, it works in Linux too), I don't understand the reason.
Therefore, in Linux, I have made the cursor fixed in a particular position on the screen.
((The pyautogui.position() in screenrecorder.py in line 115 was throwing runtime error when the tutorial_wms.py is executed on Linux.))

pr_title: [Completed] Automated tutorial for how to create a project in MSS using all the views.
pr_body:
This involves the demonstration of how to create a project with all the views, that are, top view, side view, table view and linear view.
I have tested in both windows and linux and it works smoothly.

(The previous PR opened had the random tests failing. Hence, created this new PR and closed the previous #1096 PR)

pr_title: Mscolab tutorial, TTS feature for audios
pr_body:
Created mscolab tutorial
Created audio.py file which when run in cd tutorials/ python audio.py produces mp3 files for all texts in the textfile folders.
We can choose our preffered language in which we want to translate the text file and thus creating the subsequent mp3 file for that text.
Fixed small bugs
Updated tutorials.txt requirements file
